# Editorial voice

Follow the [Microsoft Writing Style Guide](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/style-guide/welcome/)
and the [Consensys documentation style guide](https://docs-template.consensys.net/contribute/style-guide).

## Voice and tone

- Use active voice and present tense.
- Write in second person and address the reader as "you."
- Use contractions naturally.
- Refer to the reader's setup as "your node," "your validator client," or "your deployment."

## Clarity

- Lead with the most important point in each section.
- Use short, direct sentences.
- Break up long sections with headings, lists, code, or admonitions.
- Keep docs instructional and factual, not promotional.

## Sentence construction

- Front-load important words for scanning.
- Start with verbs when possible.
- Use the Oxford comma.
- Avoid filler intros like "you can" when unnecessary.

## Lists

- Use between two and seven items where practical.
- Keep list item structure parallel.

## Punctuation and formatting

- Do not use em dashes or en dashes.
- Use sentence case for headings.
- Do not end headings with periods.
- Use backticks for inline code, paths, and URLs.
- Use bold only for UI labels.

## Developer content

- List prerequisites before procedural steps.
- Provide runnable, copy-paste-friendly examples.
- Use placeholders in angle brackets for user-supplied values.

## What to avoid

- Marketing language and superlatives.
- Slang or idioms.
- Undefined jargon.
- Run-on sentences.
